				\begin{document}$$ \log \left(\frac{P\left(A,B\right)}{P(A)P(B)}\right) $$\end{document}logPABPAPB term that tends to zero with statistical independence, where P(A, B) = P(A)P(B). Mutual information and MI-based metrics have been successfully applied for the analysis of large biological data sets [44–46] (further details within
Methods/Statistical associations). Conversely, Pearson’s correlation purely measures the tendency towards a linear association, although it does provide directionality through positive/negative values.

